%T A394367 17,18,18,19,19,20,20,22,22,13,19,16,21,25,17,18,20,21,22,24,24,25,25,
%U A394367 23,26,21,23,18,24,17,19,22,23,29,25,26,27,30,30,21,23,25,26
%N A394367 Middle sides z of integer-sided triangles (x <= y <= z) having at least one integral median and such that every integral median m satisfies gcd(x, y, z, m) = 1, ordered by increasing z, then y, then x.
%C A394367 The longest and shortest sides are in A394366 and A394368, respectively. The corresponding median values m are in A394369.
%H A394367 Felix Huber, <a href="/A394367/b394367.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10098</a>
%e A394367 5 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (5, 5, 6) the median to z = 6 has length m = 4. It splits z into 3 and 3, yielding two congruent triangles (3, 4, 5), and gcd(5, 5, 6, 4) = 1.
%e A394367 8 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (7, 8, 9) the median to y = 8 has length m = 7. It splits y into 4 and 4, yielding triangles (4, 7, 7) and (4, 7, 9), and gcd(7, 8, 9, 7) = 1.
%e A394367 14 is a term because in the triangle (x, y, z) = (8, 14, 14) the medians to y = 14 and z = 14 both have length m = 9. Each splits the side into 7 and 7, yielding triangles (7, 8, 9) and (7, 9, 14), and gcd(8, 14, 14, 9) = 1.
%p A394367 # See Huber link in A394366.
